def load_data(dirname: str) -> list:
    data = []
    filenames = sorted(listdir(dirname), key=lambda x: int(x.split(".")[0]))
    for filename in filenames:
        with Image.open(f"{dirname}/{filename}", "r") as im:
            data.append(frombuffer(im.tobytes(), dtype=uint8))
    return array(data).reshape((-1, len(im.getbands())))
In [ ]:
def load_labels(filename: str) -> tuple:
    df = read_csv(filename)
    age_labels = get_dummies(df["age"])
    gender_labels = get_dummies(df["gender"])
    race_labels = get_dummies(df["race"])
    return (age_labels, gender_labels, race_labels)
In [ ]:
def scale(training_data, validation_data) -> tuple:
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    training_data = scaler.fit_transform(training_data).reshape((-1, 32, 32, 1))
    validation_data = scaler.transform(validation_data).reshape((-1, 32, 32, 1))
    return training_data, validation_data

def task_simple(func: Callable):
    def plot_history(history, title_str: str) -> None:
        plot(history["loss"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_loss"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str + " Loss Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Loss")
        show()

        plot(history["accuracy"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_accuracy"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str + " Accuracy Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Accuracy")
        show()

    def train_and_report(training_labels, validation_labels, title_str: str):
        # Create model and train
        model: Sequential = func(len(training_labels.columns))
        checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath="temp.h5",
                                     monitor="val_accuracy",
                                     mode="max",
                                     save_best_only=True)
        history = model.fit(scaled_training_data,
                         training_labels.to_numpy(),
                         100,
                         20,
                         validation_data=(scaled_validation_data, validation_labels.to_numpy()),
                         callbacks=[checkpoint])
        history = history.history

        # Create loss and accurracy plots for training and validation data
        plot_history(history, title_str)

        # Print final classification accuracy
        model = load_model("temp.h5")
        _, accuracy = model.evaluate(scaled_validation_data, validation_labels)
        print(f"Final Classification Accuracy: {accuracy}")
        remove("temp.h5")

        # Report n-class confusion matrix
        y_true = argmax(validation_labels.to_numpy(), axis=-1)
        y_pred = argmax(model.predict(scaled_validation_data), axis=-1)
        ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true, y_pred, display_labels=validation_labels.columns, xticks_rotation="vertical")
        title(title_str + " Confusion Matrix")
        xlabel("Prediction")
        ylabel("Ground Truth")
        show()


    train_and_report(training_age_labels, validation_age_labels, "Age Model")
    train_and_report(training_gender_labels, validation_gender_labels, "Gender Model")
    train_and_report(training_race_labels, validation_race_labels, "Race Model")

def build_task_1_nn(n: int):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(32, 32, 1)))
    model.add(Dense(1024, activation="tanh"))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="sigmoid"))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(n, activation="softmax"))
    model.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer=adamw.AdamW(0.0005, amsgrad=True), metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

def build_task_2_nn(n: int):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(40, 5, activation="relu", input_shape=(32,32,1)))
    model.add(MaxPool2D())
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(100, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(n, activation="softmax"))
    model.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer=adamw.AdamW(0.0005, amsgrad=True), metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

def build_task_3_nn(n: int):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(32, 7, activation="relu", input_shape=(32,32,1)))
    model.add(MaxPool2D())
    model.add(Conv2D(48, 3, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(100, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(n, activation="softmax"))
    model.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer=adamw.AdamW(0.0005, amsgrad=True), metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

def build_task_4_nn(n1: int, n2: int):
    inputs = Input((32, 32, 1))
    conv1 = Conv2D(32, 7, activation="relu")(inputs)
    max_pool = MaxPool2D()(conv1)
    conv2 = Conv2D(48, 3, activation="relu")(max_pool)
    flatten = Flatten()(conv2)

    dense_a1 = Dense(100, activation="relu")(flatten)
    dense_a2 = Dense(n1, activation="softmax", name="output_a")(dense_a1)

    dense_b1 = Dense(100, activation="relu")(flatten)
    dense_b2 = Dense(n2, activation="softmax", name="output_b")(dense_b1)

    model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=[dense_a2, dense_b2])
    model.compile(loss={"output_a": "categorical_crossentropy", "output_b": "categorical_crossentropy"}, optimizer=adamw.AdamW(0.0005, amsgrad=True), metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

def task_4(func: Callable):
    def plot_history(history, title_str: tuple) -> None:
        plot(history["loss"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_loss"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str[0] + " Loss Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Loss")
        show()

        plot(history["output_a_loss"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_output_a_loss"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str[1] + " Loss Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Loss")
        show()

        plot(history["output_b_loss"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_output_b_loss"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str[2] + " Loss Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Loss")
        show()

        plot(history["output_a_accuracy"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_output_a_accuracy"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str[1] + " Accuracy Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Accuracy")
        show()

        plot(history["output_b_accuracy"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_output_b_accuracy"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str[2] + " Accuracy Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Accuracy")
        show()

    def train_and_report(training_labels: tuple, validation_labels: tuple, title_str: tuple):
        # Create model and train
        model: Model = func(len(training_labels[0].columns), len(training_labels[1].columns))
        checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath="temp.h5",
                                     monitor="val_output_a_accuracy",
                                     mode="max",
                                     save_best_only=True)
        history = model.fit(scaled_training_data,
                         {"output_a": training_labels[0].to_numpy(), "output_b": training_labels[1].to_numpy()},
                         100,
                         20,
                         validation_data=(scaled_validation_data, {"output_a": validation_labels[0].to_numpy(), "output_b": validation_labels[1].to_numpy()}),
                         callbacks=[checkpoint])
        history = history.history

        # Create loss and accurracy plots for training and validation data
        plot_history(history, title_str)

        # Print final classification accuracy
        model = load_model("temp.h5")
        _, _, _, accuracy_a, accuracy_b = model.evaluate(scaled_validation_data, {"output_a": validation_labels[0].to_numpy(), "output_b": validation_labels[1].to_numpy()})
        print(f"Final Classification Accuracy for {title_str[1]}: {accuracy_a}")
        print(f"Final Classification Accuracy for {title_str[2]}: {accuracy_b}")
        remove("temp.h5")

        # Report n-class confusion matrix
        y_true_a = argmax(validation_labels[0].to_numpy(), axis=-1)
        y_true_b = argmax(validation_labels[1].to_numpy(), axis=-1)
        y_pred = model.predict(scaled_validation_data)
        y_pred_a = argmax(y_pred[0], axis=-1)
        y_pred_b = argmax(y_pred[1], axis=-1)

        ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true_a, y_pred_a, display_labels=validation_labels[0].columns, xticks_rotation="vertical")
        title(title_str[1] + " Confusion Matrix")
        xlabel("Prediction")
        ylabel("Ground Truth")
        show()

        ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true_b, y_pred_b, display_labels=validation_labels[1].columns, xticks_rotation="vertical")
        title(title_str[2] + " Confusion Matrix")
        xlabel("Prediction")
        ylabel("Ground Truth")
        show()


    train_and_report((training_age_labels, training_gender_labels), (validation_age_labels, validation_gender_labels), ("Age and Gender Model", "Age Model Branch", "Gender Model Branch"))

def build_task_5_nn() -> tuple:
    latent_dim = 5

    def sampling(args):
        z_mean, z_log_var = args
        epsilon = random_normal(shape=(shape(z_mean)[0], latent_dim))
        return z_mean + exp(0.5 * z_log_var) * epsilon

    # Encoder
    encoder_inputs = Input((32, 32, 1))
    encoder_conv1 = Conv2D(32, 7, strides=2, activation="relu", padding="same")(encoder_inputs)
    encoder_conv2 = Conv2D(48, 3, strides=2, activation="relu", padding="same")(encoder_conv1)
    encoder_flatten = Flatten()(encoder_conv2)
    encoder_dense = Dense(16, activation="relu")(encoder_flatten)
    z_mean = Dense(latent_dim, name="z_mean")(encoder_dense)
    z_log_var = Dense(latent_dim, name="z_log_var")(encoder_dense)
    z = Lambda(sampling, name='z')([z_mean, z_log_var])
    encoder = Model(inputs=encoder_inputs, outputs=[z_mean, z_log_var, z], name="encoder")

    # Decoder
    latent_inputs = Input((latent_dim,))
    decoder_dense = Dense(8 * 8 * 48, activation="relu")(latent_inputs)
    decoder_reshape = Reshape((8, 8, 48))(decoder_dense)
    decoder_conv2dtranspose1 = Conv2DTranspose(48, 3, strides=2, activation="relu", padding="same")(decoder_reshape)
    decoder_conv2dtranspose2 = Conv2DTranspose(32, 7, strides=2, activation="relu", padding="same")(decoder_conv2dtranspose1)
    decoder_conv2dtranspose3 = Conv2DTranspose(1, 7, activation="sigmoid", padding="same")(decoder_conv2dtranspose2)
    decoder = Model(inputs=latent_inputs, outputs=decoder_conv2dtranspose3, name="decoder")

    # VAE
    vae_output = decoder(encoder(encoder_inputs)[2])
    vae = Model(inputs=encoder_inputs, outputs=vae_output, name="vae")
    reconstruction_loss = reduce_mean(reduce_sum(mse(encoder_inputs, vae_output), axis=(1, 2)))
    kl_loss = -0.5 * (1 + z_log_var - square(z_mean) - exp(z_log_var))
    kl_loss = reduce_mean(reduce_sum(kl_loss, axis=1))
    vae_loss = reconstruction_loss + kl_loss
    vae.add_loss(vae_loss)
    vae.compile(optimizer=adamw.AdamW(0.0005, amsgrad=True))
    return encoder, decoder, vae

def task_5(func: Callable):
    def plot_history(history, title_str: str) -> None:
        plot(history["loss"], "o-")
        plot(history["val_loss"], "o-")
        legend(["Training", "Validation"])
        title(title_str + " Loss Over Time")
        xlabel("Epoch")
        ylabel("Loss")
        show()

    def train_and_report(title_str: str):
        # Create model and train
        encoder, decoder, vae = func()
        history = vae.fit(scaled_training_data,
                          None,
                          100,
                          10,
                          validation_data=(scaled_validation_data, None))
        history = history.history

        # Create loss and accurracy plots for training and validation data
        plot_history(history, title_str)

        # Generate and display a 5x5 of faces
        figure(figsize=(5, 5))
        _, axs = subplots(5, 5)

        _, _, z = encoder.predict(scaled_training_data)
        rng = default_rng()
        pictures = rng.choice(decoder.predict(z), 25, replace=False)
        print(z.shape)

        for i in range(5):
            for j in range(5):
                axs[i, j].imshow(pictures[i * 5 + j].reshape(32, 32), cmap="gray")
                axs[i, j].axis("off")
        show()

    train_and_report("Variable Auto Encoder Model")

Report¶

Introduction¶

The objective of this project was to explore how to create various architectures of Neural Networks through Tensorflow/Keras' API. The scenario is classification of various face attributes (age, gender, and race) based on the FairFace dataset containing 86,744 training face images and 10,954 validation images. By using this scenario for each architecture, we can observe the kind of differences that result from different architectures. Additionally, we explore generative models by making a variational auto encoders to generating new faces.

Introduction to Networks¶

Task 1 Network¶

The task 1 neural network is a traditional fully connected feed forward type network. The first layer is a Flatten layer which takes the inputted image which has dimensions of (32, 32, 1) and flattens it into 1024 nodes so that it can be use by the next layer. The second layer is a Dense layer with 1024 nodes, presumably 1 for each pixel from the image. It uses the tanh activation function. The third layer is another Dense layer with 512 nodes, half the previous, and uses the sigmoid activation function. The fourth layer is a Dense layer with 100 nodes with the relu activation function. The final layer is also a Dense layer with n node where n is the number of classes for the face attribute we are trying to classify. It uses the softmax activation function, typical for classification tasks. The model is compiled with categorical_crossentropy as its loss function and uses the AMSGrad version of the newer AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of 0.0005 (which we found through trial and error to perform well). The reason we chose AMSGrad AdamW is due to the benefits it provides. AMSGrad, based on the paper behind it, shows that AMSGrad addresses some convergance issues that Adam has and tends to provide better emperical performance. AdamW was chosen based on its paper that demonstrates their decoupling of decaying weights improved emperical performace. A couple comparison runs with SGD and Adam showed AdamW to perform better.

Task 2 Network¶

Task 2's neural network is a traditional convolutional type netwok. Layer 1 is a Conv2D layer with 40 feature detectors with a kernel size of 5x5. It uses the relu activation function and because it is a Conv2D layer, it can directly accept the image as a (32, 32, 1). Following is MaxPool2D layer, a typical followup to convolutional layers. The third layer is just a Flatten layer to link the 3 dimensional data outputted by the previous layers with the fully connected layers that follow. The fourth and fifth layers are the same as task 1's fourth and fifth layers. This network is also compiled with the same loss function and optimizer as task 1.

Task 3 Network¶

Task 3 gave us the freedom to tweak the layers and parameters of Task 2's network. The first change we made was changing the first layer (a Conv2D) to use 32 feature detectors instead of 40 with a kernel size of 7x7 instead of 5x5. The intent was to identify fewer, but larger features from the image of the face. The second change was adding another Conv2D layer after the MaxPool2D layer with 48 feature detectors and a kernel size of 3x3 with the intent that it would identify the finer features from the previous layer before handed it off to the fully connected layer after it. It used the relu activation function chosen simply because the first convolutional layer also used it.

Task 4 Network¶

Task 4 was unique as it make us forgo the Sequential model and had us classify two attributes at the same time (still centering around a convolutional type network). We decided to use Task 3's network up till the first Dense layer where we decopuled the different parts of the network for each attribute we wanted to classify. Each branch had 2 Dense layer with 100 nodes and n node (n = number of classes), respectively. The first Dense layer use the relu activation function and the second softmax. Both branches used categorical_crossentropy and the whole network was trained with AdamW with the same parameters as the previous networks.

Task 5 Network¶

Task 5 was to make a variational autoencoder (VAE). A VAE model is made of two submodels, an encoder and a decoder. The encoder starts with a Conv2D layer with 32 feature detectors, a kernel size of 7x7, stride of 2, relu activation function, and same padding. Following is a Conv2D layer with 48 feature detectors, a kernel size of 3x3, stride of 2, relu activation function, and same padding. Aside from the stride and padding, these layers are the same as task 3's with the MaxPool2D layer removed. The next layers are a Flatten layer and a Dense layer with 16 nodes and the relu activation function. Now, in order for the VAE to be a VAE, there are 3 layers characteristic of a VAE. The first two are Dense layer with latent_dim nodes (latent_dim = 5 for this task) and sit side by side getting input from the same layer (the Dense layer with 16 nodes). Both of these layers feed into the last layer with is a custom layer (Lambda) that given the previous two layers (called z_mean and z_log_var respectively), call a sampling function that conducts a reparameterizatino trick. The decoder is meant to be the inverse of the encoder. It starts with a Dense layer with 8 * 8 * 48 node and the relu activation function. The node count reflects the output of the last Conv2D layer in the encoder. Layer 2 is a Reshape that reshapes the input from the previous layer into a (8, 8, 48) tensor. That gets passed to a Conv2DTranspose with 48 feature detectors, a kernel size of 3x3, stride of 2, relu activation function, and same padding, the same parameters as the last Conv2D layer in the encoder. The fourth layer is a Conv2DTranspose layer with the same parameters as the 1st Conv2D layer of the encoder. The fifth layer is a Conv2DTranspose layer with 1 feature detecter (as the input had 1 channel) and a kernel size of 7x7 to match the previous layer with a sigmoid activation function and same padding. The encoder's input and decoder's output (given the Lambda layer output of the encoder) are joined to make the VAE model. This model is given a custom loss function with two parts (that are summed together), the reconstruction loss and the kl divergense loss. The reconstruction loss is mean squared error between the input to the VAE and what the VAE outputs reduced by taking its sum followed by its mean.

Conclusion¶

First and foremost, for faces, and images in general, convolutional neural networks do a much better job at discovering useful features to distinguish one class from another. Second, parameters matter. We saw a delta as large as 3.5% when using different optimizers with different learning rates. Another interesting obsevation we saw was how quickly (~3-5 epochs) Task 4's branch model reached very low losses compared to the sequential model. Lastly, it seems that VAEs are expensive to train and run which makes sense when considering the copmlexity of what they are designed to achieve. It's likely that other generative types of models are also expensive because of the nature of trying to extrapolate patterns in so many dimensions.

How to run code¶

Just run all the cells top down. Make sure you have all the appropriate python packages installed. In particular, ensure the tensorflow package is at least version 2.12.0 (the latest version at time of writing) as the optimizer used AdamW is not available in older versions.
